        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       President Trump has <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-jul-25-spotlight-h1-1-lifted-us-sanctions" target="_blank">lifted US sanctions</a> on Syria, ending a two-decade blockade on Syriaâ€™s gateway to international funds. The lifting of the sanctions withdraws restrictions on key state institutions, such as the central bank. However, targeted sanctions on former President Bashar al-Assad, human rights abusers, and extremist groups like ISIS and Iranian proxies remain.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
    The White House said this measure aims to promote peace and stability. Syrians <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-jul-25-spotlight-h1-2-celebrated-the-announcement" target="_blank">celebrated the announcement</a> in Damascus, followed by a speech by transitional President Ahmed al-Sharaa, who led an Islamist-backed effort that ousted Assad in December. Syrian officials praised the decision as a significant breakthrough for reconstruction and the return of refugees. </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       Trump previously eased some of the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-jul-25-spotlight-h1-3-restrictions-in-may" target="_blank">restrictions in May</a> due to pressure from Saudi Arabia and Turkey. The US is also reviewing terrorism-related designations, including those of HTS and al-Sharaa himself. </p>
        </mj-text>
