    Was the US airstrike on Iran effective? 
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
       Summary: The US and European intelligence indicate Iran's uranium stockpile likely survived the attacks.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          When the US dropped 14 bunker bombs on <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-01-07-2025-irans-nuclear-facility" target="_blank">Iranâ€™s nuclear facilities</a>, President Trump asserted that they had neutralized Iranâ€™s nuclear ambitions. However, a preliminary US intelligence report stated that the strikes caused significant damage, rather than <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-01-07-2025-complete-destruction" target="_blank">complete destruction</a>. Currently, there is a doubt over whether the attacks destroyed Tehranâ€™s 408.6 kg reserve of enriched uranium. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Satellite images revealed tunnels and truck movements just days before the attack, suggesting that Iran may have moved the uranium stockpile. While the attack disabled Iranâ€™s centrifuge systems, experts warn that Iran still has the skills and secret facilities <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-jul-25-analysis-h1-8-to-restart-enrichment" target="_blank">to restart enrichment</a> to make nuclear bombs. They also assert that enrichment from 60% to weapons-grade 90% could take as little as five days. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Experts believe that while Iranâ€™s nuclear ambitions faced a setback, the actual delay may be months rather than years. Recently, Tehran rejected an appeal for Rafael Grossi to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-jul-25-analysis-h1-9-visit-nuclear-facilities" target="_blank">visit nuclear facilities</a> bombed by Israel and the US during the conflict, adding to the uncertainty over the extent of the US attack. Iranian lawmakers voted in favor of a bill to suspend cooperation with the IAEA.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
