          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
    How did Canada become independent? 
 
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/fathers-of-confederation-canada-1867-independence.jpg" alt="The Fathers of Confederation drafted the British North America Act, leading to Canada's independence in 1867" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>The Fathers of Confederation drafted the British North America Bill, leading to Canada's independence in 1867. Credits: Robert Harris</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Canada did not fight a war for independence. Its break from Britain happened over more than a century through negotiation and legislation. July 1 commemorates the anniversary of Canadaâ€™s Confederation in 1867. Canada became a self-governing Dominion (self-governing nation within the British Empire) with the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-jul-25-foundations-h1-16-constitution-bill" target="_blank">Constitution Bill</a>, uniting Ontario, Quebec, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick. </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        By 1931, Britain granted Canada and other Dominions legislative independence, thereby granting Canada full control over its foreign policy. In 1982, the British <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-jul-25-foundations-h1-17-granted-full-sovereignty" target="_blank">granted full sovereignty</a> rights. </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-jul-25-foundations-h1-18-canada-bill" target="_blank">Canada Bill</a> formally ended the British Parliament's ability to legislate for Canada. This brought the Constitution to Canada, including the Charter of Rights and Freedoms, which finalized complete judicial independence.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Canada remains part of the British Commonwealth and is eligible to participate in specific programs with the UK. Members of the British royal family frequently attend Canada Day. </p>
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       <strong><i>Happy Canada Day to our Canadian readers!</i></strong></p>

        </mj-text>
